      <bioghist id="aspace_59cc443c6eee19b9d73aa887d2a8e2a1">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>George S. Lewis was a British private with the Bearer Company, Imperial Yeomanry Field Hospital, South African Field Office. He was captured by Boers near Roodwal en route from Bloemfontein to Johannesburg in May, 1900 and was held prisoner for four days before being rescued by Lord Methuen. Lewis was subsequently confined to the Johannesburg Hospital for six weeks. Upon his recovery, he worked at the No. 3 Model School Hospital from mid-August to November, tending British and Boer wounded. Lewis then traveled to the Maitland Camp at Cape Town to await shipment home on board the S. S. "Orotava."</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_b295404f94c13d8b80c67422c4bb4c78">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The George S. Lewis Papers consist of correspondence between Lewis and his family and friends. The letters chronicle his daily routine as well as noteworthy events, such as the collision between his troopship, S. S. "Winkfield", and the Union Castle S. S. "Mexican" near Cape Town on April 5, 1900. Photographs of Lewis and memorabilia complete the collection which was received in May, 1994.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_4251970d9836317d40d55ed5af45f0c7">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The papers are arranged by record type.</p>  
